Below is one ARC‐style task that uses simple arithmetic on grids. In this task the rule is: “Leave the border cells unchanged, but for every interior cell (i.e. not in the first or last row or column), add 1 to its current numeric value.”

For efficiency the grids are 10×10. (Note: cells are accessed as grid[row][column].)

────────────────────────────
Task Description

A grid is given in which the values along the outer edge (first and last row and first and last column) are “protected.” All other cells (the interior) must be incremented by 1. In other words, if a cell is not on the border, then its new value is add(cell, 1) using the provided DSL function add from Michael Hodel’s DSL.

Your ARC‐task consists of three training examples and one test example below.

────────────────────────────
Analogy

This ARC‐problem is analogous to “incrementing only the non‐perimeter (interior) cells” in a grid. In every example the transformation is performed only on the inner cells while the border remains intact. Use the DSL’s add function for numerical addition.

────────────────────────────
Program with Hodel DSL

Below is one possible solution written in the style of Michael Hodel’s DSL:

------------------------------------------------
from arc_types import *

def solve(grid: Grid) -> Grid:
    # Get dimensions of the grid
    h = len(grid)
    w = len(grid[0])
    # Create a copy of the grid as a list of lists
    new_grid = [list(row) for row in grid]
    # For each cell in the grid
    for i in range(h):
        for j in range(w):
            # Check if the cell is an interior cell
            if i != 0 and i != h - 1 and j != 0 and j != w - 1:
                # Increment its value by 1 using the DSL 'add'
                new_grid[i][j] = add(new_grid[i][j], 1)
    # Convert back to tuple-of-tuples to form a Grid
    return tuple(tuple(row) for row in new_grid)

# Example usage:
# Given an input grid (e.g., one of the training inputs),
# the function 'solve' returns the transformed grid.
------------------------------------------------

This DSL-based program goes through every cell and applies the rule accordingly.

• Input grids are 10×10.

• Each interior cell is replaced with add(cell, 1).
• Three training examples and one test example illustrate the rule.
